<!-- Q1 -->
<div class="problem" id="q1">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">1</span>
    <span class="answer-badge">Answer: A</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Integration by Long Division + Partial Fractions</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Evaluate \(\displaystyle\int \frac{3x^2-7x-4}{x-3}\,dx\).</p>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Step 1 — Polynomial long division</div>
      <p>The degree of the numerator equals the degree of the denominator + 1, so divide first.</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\frac{3x^2-7x-4}{x-3} = 3x+2 + \frac{2}{x-3}\]
      </div>
      <p>Check: \((3x+2)(x-3)+2 = 3x^2-9x+2x-6+2 = 3x^2-7x-4\). ✓</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Step 2 — Integrate term by term</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\int\left(3x+2+\frac{2}{x-3}\right)dx = \tfrac{3}{2}x^2+2x+2\ln|x-3|+C\]
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="key-insight">The remainder after division is \(2\), not \(-10\), which rules out (B).</div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#answer-key-a">↑ Return to answer key</a></div>
</div>

<!-- Q2 -->
<div class="problem" id="q2">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">2</span>
    <span class="answer-badge">Answer: A</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Definite Integral with Variable Upper Limit / FTC</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Evaluate \(\displaystyle\int_0^{x^2} e^{3t}\,dt\).</p>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Antiderivative and evaluation</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\int_0^{x^2} e^{3t}\,dt = \left[\frac{e^{3t}}{3}\right]_0^{x^2} = \frac{e^{3x^2}}{3} - \frac{1}{3} = \frac{1}{3}\!\left(e^{3x^2}-1\right)\]
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="distractor-note">Forgetting to divide by 3 (chain rule for integration) gives choice (C) \(= 2xe^{3x^2}\) — this is actually the derivative of the correct answer via FTC Part 1, not the integral itself.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#answer-key-a">↑ Return to answer key</a></div>
</div>

<!-- Q3 -->
<div class="problem" id="q3">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">3</span>
    <span class="answer-badge">Answer: C</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Slope of Tangent Line / Chain Rule</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Find the slope of the tangent to \(y = e^{6x} - \sin(4x)\) at \(x=0\).</p>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Differentiate using the Chain Rule</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[y' = 6e^{6x} - 4\cos(4x)\]
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Evaluate at x = 0</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[y'(0) = 6e^{0} - 4\cos(0) = 6(1) - 4(1) = 2\]
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#answer-key-a">↑ Return to answer key</a></div>
</div>

<!-- Q4 -->
<div class="problem" id="q4">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">4</span>
    <span class="answer-badge">Answer: D</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">L'Hôpital's Rule</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Evaluate \(\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{2e^{5x}-5e^{2x}+3}{x^2-2\cos(2x)+2}\).</p>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Check indeterminate form</div>
      <p>At \(x=0\): numerator \(= 2-5+3=0\); denominator \(= 0-2+2=0\). Form \(\tfrac{0}{0}\).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">First application of L'Hôpital</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\frac{10e^{5x}-10e^{2x}}{2x+4\sin(2x)}\xrightarrow{x\to 0}\frac{0}{0}\]
      </div>
      <p>Still indeterminate — apply L'Hôpital a second time.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Second application of L'Hôpital</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\frac{50e^{5x}-20e^{2x}}{2+8\cos(2x)}\xrightarrow{x\to 0}\frac{50-20}{2+8} = \frac{30}{10} = 3\]
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="key-insight">Answer: <strong>(D) 3</strong>.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#answer-key-a">↑ Return to answer key</a></div>
</div>

<!-- Q5 -->
<div class="problem" id="q5">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">5</span>
    <span class="answer-badge">Answer: C</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Series Convergence Tests</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Which of the series I, II, III converge?</p>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Series I</div>
      <p>This is a \(p\)-series with \(p = \tfrac{2}{3} < 1\). <strong>Diverges.</strong></p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Series II</div>
      <p>Compare to \(\frac{k}{k^3} = \frac{1}{k^2}\) (a convergent \(p\)-series, \(p=2\)). By Limit Comparison Test with \(b_k = \frac{1}{k^2}\):</p>
      <div class="math-display">\[\lim_{k\to\infty}\frac{k/(k^3+5k+1)}{1/k^2} = \lim_{k\to\infty}\frac{k^3}{k^3+5k+1} = 1 > 0\]</div>
      <p><strong>Converges.</strong></p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Series III</div>
      <p>Alternating series. Check: \(\frac{1}{k}\) is decreasing and \(\to 0\). By the Alternating Series Test, <strong>converges</strong> (conditionally).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="key-insight">Series I diverges; Series II and III converge. Answer: <strong>(C) II and III</strong>.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#answer-key-a">↑ Return to answer key</a></div>
</div>

<!-- Q6 -->
<div class="problem" id="q6">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">6</span>
    <span class="answer-badge">Answer: A</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Integration by Partial Fractions</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Evaluate \(\displaystyle\int\frac{4x-1}{2x^2-x-1}\,dx\).</p>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Factor denominator</div>
      <div class="math-display">\[2x^2-x-1 = (2x+1)(x-1)\]</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Partial fraction decomposition</div>
      <div class="math-display">\[\frac{4x-1}{(x-1)(2x+1)} = \frac{A}{x-1}+\frac{B}{2x+1}\]</div>
      <p>\(4x-1 = A(2x+1)+B(x-1)\).</p>
      <p>Set \(x=1\): \(3 = 3A \Rightarrow A=1\).</p>
      <p>Set \(x=-\tfrac{1}{2}\): \(-3 = -\tfrac{3}{2}B \Rightarrow B=2\).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Integrate</div>
      <div class="math-display">\[\int\left(\frac{1}{x-1}+\frac{2}{2x+1}\right)dx = \ln|x-1|+\ln|2x+1|+C = \ln|(x-1)(2x+1)|+C\]</div>
    </div>
    <div class="key-insight">Answer is <strong>(A)</strong>: \(\ln|(x-1)(2x+1)|+C\).</div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#answer-key-a">↑ Return to answer key</a></div>
</div>

<!-- Q7 -->
<div class="problem" id="q7">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">7</span>
    <span class="answer-badge">Answer: B</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Telescoping Series</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Find \(\displaystyle\sum_{k=1}^\infty\!\left(\frac{1}{k}-\frac{1}{k+2}\right)\).</p>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Write partial sums — telescoping</div>
      <p>Partial sum \(S_n = \left(1-\tfrac{1}{3}\right)+\left(\tfrac{1}{2}-\tfrac{1}{4}\right)+\left(\tfrac{1}{3}-\tfrac{1}{5}\right)+\cdots\)</p>
      <p>The pattern telescopes, leaving only the first two positive terms minus the last two negative terms:</p>
      <div class="math-display">\[S_n = 1+\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{n+1}-\frac{1}{n+2}\]</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Take the limit</div>
      <div class="math-display">\[\lim_{n\to\infty} S_n = 1+\frac{1}{2}-0-0 = \frac{3}{2} = 1.5\]</div>
    </div>
    <div class="key-insight">Answer: <strong>(B) 1.5</strong>. Note the gap of 2 in the telescoping means two initial terms survive.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#answer-key-a">↑ Return to answer key</a></div>
</div>

<!-- Q8 -->
<div class="problem" id="q8">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">8</span>
    <span class="answer-badge">Answer: B</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Points of Inflection / Second Derivative</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Given \(f''(x)=x^2(x-1)\sqrt{x+1}\), find where \(f\) has inflection points.</p>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Find sign changes of f ''(x)</div>
      <p>Domain: \(x\geq -1\) (square root). Zeros of \(f''\): \(x=-1\), \(x=0\) (multiplicity 2), and \(x=1\).</p>
      <p>At \(x=0\): \(x^2\geq 0\) for all \(x\), so the \(x^2\) factor does not change sign. The sign of \(f''\) near \(x=0\) is therefore governed entirely by \((x-1)\sqrt{x+1}\), which is negative on both sides of \(x=0\). Since \(f''\) does not change sign at \(x=0\), this is <strong>not</strong> an inflection point.</p>
      <p>At \(x=1\): \((x-1)\) changes sign from \(-\) to \(+\), while \(x^2>0\) and \(\sqrt{x+1}>0\). So \(f''\) changes sign. <strong>Inflection point at \(x=1\).</strong></p>
      <p>At \(x=-1\): left endpoint of the domain — not an interior point, so not an inflection point.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="key-insight">The only inflection point is at \(x=1\). Answer: <strong>(B) 1 only</strong>.</div>
    <div class="distractor-note">A common error is to conclude \(x=0\) is an inflection point because \(f''(0)=0\). A zero of \(f''\) is only an inflection point if \(f''\) <em>changes sign</em> there. The even multiplicity of the factor \(x^2\) means \(f''\) keeps the same sign on both sides of \(x=0\).</div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#answer-key-a">↑ Return to answer key</a></div>
</div>

<!-- Q9 -->
<div class="problem" id="q9">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">9</span>
    <span class="answer-badge">Answer: C</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">FTC / u-Substitution with Antiderivative Notation</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>If \(F'(x)=f(x)\), evaluate \(\displaystyle\int_2^5 f(3x+2)\,dx\).</p>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Substitution</div>
      <p>Let \(u=3x+2\). Then \(du = 3\,dx\), so \(dx = \tfrac{du}{3}\). Limits: \(x=2\Rightarrow u=8\); \(x=5\Rightarrow u=17\).</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\int_2^5 f(3x+2)\,dx = \frac{1}{3}\int_8^{17}f(u)\,du = \frac{1}{3}\left[F(u)\right]_8^{17} = \frac{1}{3}F(17)-\frac{1}{3}F(8)\]
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="key-insight">Answer: <strong>(C)</strong> \(\tfrac{1}{3}F(17)-\tfrac{1}{3}F(8)\).</div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#answer-key-a">↑ Return to answer key</a></div>
</div>

<!-- Q10 -->
<div class="problem" id="q10">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">10</span>
    <span class="answer-badge">Answer: D</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Geometric Series — Sum</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Find \(\displaystyle\sum_{k=1}^\infty \frac{3^{k+2}}{5^{k+1}}\).</p>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Rewrite to identify a and r</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\frac{3^{k+2}}{5^{k+1}} = \frac{9\cdot 3^k}{5\cdot 5^k} = \frac{9}{5}\left(\frac{3}{5}\right)^k\]
      </div>
      <p>This is a geometric series with first term \(a = \frac{9}{5}\cdot\frac{3}{5} = \frac{27}{25}\) and ratio \(r=\frac{3}{5}\).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Apply geometric series formula</div>
      <p>The sum starts at \(k=1\), so the first term is \(a=\frac{9}{5}\cdot\frac{3}{5}=\frac{27}{25}\) and ratio \(r=\frac{3}{5}\):</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[S = \frac{a}{1-r} = \frac{27/25}{2/5} = \frac{27}{25}\cdot\frac{5}{2} = \frac{27}{10}\]
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="key-insight">Answer: <strong>(D) \(\dfrac{27}{10}\)</strong>.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#answer-key-a">↑ Return to answer key</a></div>
</div>

