    <p>The base is the region bounded by \(y=\sqrt{x}\), \(x=3\), \(x=1\), and the \(x\)-axis. Cross sections perpendicular to the \(x\)-axis are squares. Find the volume.</p>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Side length of each square</div>
      <p>At position \(x\), the side length is \(s = \sqrt{x}\), so the cross-sectional area is \(A(x) = (\sqrt{x})^2 = x\).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-label">Integrate</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[V = \int_1^3 x\,dx = \left[\frac{x^2}{2}\right]_1^3 = \frac{9}{2}-\frac{1}{2} = 4\]
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="key-insight">Answer: <strong>(C) 4</strong>.</div>
