      <p>The slopes in the field are always greater than or equal to zero — no negative slopes appear anywhere. This rules out any equation whose right-hand side can be negative.</p>
      <p>For \(\dfrac{dy}{dt}=t^2\): since \(t^2\geq 0\) for all \(t\), all slopes are non-negative, consistent with the field. The slopes are zero along the vertical line \(t=0\) and increase symmetrically as \(|t|\) grows, independent of \(y\) — also consistent with the field showing constant slope along each vertical line.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="key-insight">Answer: <strong>(B)</strong> \(\dfrac{dy}{dt}=t^2\).</div>
  </div>
