<!-- FR 1 -->
<div class="problem" id="fr1">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">FR 1</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Polar Curves — Area, Maximum Distance, Rate of Change</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>\(r_1(\theta)=2+3\sin\theta+4\cos\theta,\quad r_2(\theta)=2+6\cos\theta\) on \(0\leq\theta\leq\pi/2\). Let \(S\) be the shaded region bounded by the two curves, the \(x\)-axis, and the \(y\)-axis. Curves intersect at point \(P\).</p>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(a) Area of \(S\)</div>
      <p>Find the angle \(\theta_P\) at which \(r_1=r_2\). Setting equal:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[2+3\sin\theta+4\cos\theta = 2+6\cos\theta \implies 3\sin\theta = 2\cos\theta \implies \tan\theta = \tfrac{2}{3}\]
      </div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\theta_P = \arctan\!\left(\tfrac{2}{3}\right)\approx 0.588\]
      </div>
      <p>The region \(S\) is bounded by \(r_1\) from \(\theta=0\) to \(\theta_P\) and by \(r_2\) from \(\theta_P\) to \(\pi/2\):</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[A = \frac{1}{2}\int_0^{\theta_P}\left[r_1(\theta)\right]^2 d\theta + \frac{1}{2}\int_{\theta_P}^{\pi/2}\left[r_2(\theta)\right]^2 d\theta\]
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(b) Point on \(r_1\) farthest from the origin</div>
      <p>The distance from the origin in polar coordinates is simply \(r_1(\theta)\). Maximize:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\frac{dr_1}{d\theta} = 3\cos\theta - 4\sin\theta = 0 \implies \tan\theta = \frac{3}{4} \implies \theta = \arctan\!\left(\tfrac{3}{4}\right)\approx 0.6435\]
      </div>
      <p>Verify this is a maximum: \(r_1''(\theta^*) < 0\). ✓</p>
      <p>At \(\theta=\arctan(3/4)\): \(\sin\theta=\tfrac{3}{5}\) and \(\cos\theta=\tfrac{4}{5}\) (from the 3-4-5 right triangle).</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[r_1 = 2+3\cdot\tfrac{3}{5}+4\cdot\tfrac{4}{5} = 2+\tfrac{9}{5}+\tfrac{16}{5} = 2+5 = 7\]
      </div>
      <p>The maximum distance is 7, occurring at \(\theta=\arctan(3/4)\).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(c) Rate of change of radial distance between curves at \(\theta=\pi/6\)</div>
      <p>The radial distance between the two curves is \(D(\theta)=r_2(\theta)-r_1(\theta)=2\cos\theta-3\sin\theta\), since \(r_2 > r_1\) on this interval.</p>
      <p>Given \(\dfrac{d\theta}{dt}=\dfrac{1}{3}\):</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\frac{dD}{dt} = \frac{dD}{d\theta}\cdot\frac{d\theta}{dt} = (-2\sin\theta-3\cos\theta)\cdot\frac{1}{3}\]
      </div>
      <p>Substituting \(\theta=\pi/6\), \(\sin\tfrac{\pi}{6}=\tfrac{1}{2}\), \(\cos\tfrac{\pi}{6}=\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\), and \(\dfrac{d\theta}{dt}=\tfrac{1}{3}\):</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\frac{dD}{dt} = -2\!\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\!\left(\frac{1}{3}\right) - 3\!\left(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)\!\left(\frac{1}{3}\right) = -\frac{1}{3}-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} = \frac{-2-3\sqrt{3}}{6}\approx -1.199\]
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#top">↑ Return to top</a></div>
</div>

<!-- FR 2 -->
<div class="problem" id="fr2">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">FR 2</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Rate/Accumulation — Unprocessed Orders</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Orders received at \(r(t)=400\sqrt{9+4t-t^2}\) orders/hr, processed at 1200/hr. Initial backlog: 2000 orders. \(0\leq t\leq 5\).</p>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(a) \(\displaystyle\int_3^4 r(t)\,dt\) — meaning and value</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\int_3^4 r(t)\,dt = \int_3^4 400\sqrt{9+4t-t^2}\,dt\]
      </div>
      <p>Using a calculator: \(\displaystyle\int_3^4 400\sqrt{9+4t-t^2}\,dt \approx 1305.295\), so approximately <strong>1305 complete orders</strong>.</p>
      <p><strong>Meaning:</strong> This is the total number of orders received between \(t=3\) and \(t=4\) hours after noon (i.e., between 3:00 PM and 4:00 PM).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(b) \(N(t)\) — number of unprocessed orders at time \(t\)</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[N(t) = (2000 - 1200t) + \int_0^t 400\sqrt{9+4x-x^2}\,dx\]
      </div>
      <p>The first term \((2000-1200t)\) accounts for the initial backlog of 2000 orders minus orders processed at 1200/hr. The integral gives the total number of orders received from time 0 to time \(t\).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(c) When is \(N(t)\) maximum on \([0,5]\)?</div>
      <p>\(N'(t) = r(t)-1200=0\) when \(400\sqrt{9+4t-t^2}=1200\), i.e., \(\sqrt{9+4t-t^2}=3\).</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[9+4t-t^2=9 \implies t(4-t)=0 \implies t=0\text{ or }t=4\]
      </div>
      <p>On the interval \(0 &lt; t &lt; 4\), we confirm \(r(t)&gt;1200\): at \(t=2\), \(400\sqrt{9+8-4}=400\sqrt{13}\approx 1442&gt;1200\). ✓</p>
      <p>So \(N'(t)>0\) on \((0,4)\) and \(N'(t)<0\) on \((4,5)\). Maximum at \(t=4\) hours (4:00 PM).</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#top">↑ Return to top</a></div>
</div>

