<!-- FR 3 -->
<div class="problem" id="fr3">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">FR 3</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Parametric Motion — Position, Arc Length, Target Intercept</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Rocket position \((x(t),y(t))\) from \((5,10)\); \(x'(t)=6t-3t^2,\;y'(t)=6-2t\).</p>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(a) Slope and acceleration at \(t=1\)</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[x'(1)=6-3=3,\quad y'(1)=6-2=4\]
      </div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\text{slope}=\frac{dy}{dx}\bigg|_{t=1}=\frac{y'(1)}{x'(1)}=\frac{4}{3}\]
      </div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[x''(t)=6-6t\big|_{t=1}=0,\quad y''(t)=-2\]
      </div>
      <p>Acceleration vector at \(t=1\): \(\langle 0,-2\rangle\).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(b) Arc length from \(t=1\) to \(t=4\)</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[L = \int_1^4\sqrt{[x'(t)]^2+[y'(t)]^2}\,dt = \int_1^4\sqrt{(6t-3t^2)^2+(6-2t)^2}\,dt\]
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(c) Does the rocket reach \((-45, 15)\)?</div>
      <p>Find position by integrating:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[x(t)=5+\int_0^t(6s-3s^2)\,ds=5+3t^2-t^3\]
        \[y(t)=10+\int_0^t(6-2s)\,ds=10+6t-t^2\]
      </div>
      <p>Set \(y(t)=15\): \(t^2-6t+5=0\Rightarrow(t-1)(t-5)=0\Rightarrow t=1\) or \(t=5\).</p>
      <p>At \(t=5\): \(x(5)=5+75-125=-45\). ✓</p>
      <p><strong>Yes</strong>, the rocket reaches \((-45,15)\) at \(t=5\).</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#top">↑ Return to top</a></div>
</div>

<!-- FR 4 -->
<div class="problem" id="fr4">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">FR 4</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Piecewise-Defined Derivative — Analysis of \(f\), \(g\), \(h\)</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>\(f\) is defined on \([0,16]\) with \(f(0)=-3\). The graph of \(f'\) consists of 4 line segments. Also given: \(g(x)=(f(x))^2\), \(h(x)=xe^{-0.25f(x)}\), and \(y=\tfrac{4}{x}\) intersects the graph of \(f'\) at points \(P\) and \(Q\).</p>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(a) Relative minimum, relative maximum, or neither at \(x=12\)?</div>
      <p>Inspecting the graph of \(f'\), the \(y\)-coordinate of \(f'\) is 0 at \(x=12\), confirming a critical number. The values of \(f'\) are positive immediately to the left of \(x=12\) and negative immediately to the right.</p>
      <p>Therefore, by the First Derivative Test, since \(f'(x)>0\) on \((4,12)\) and \(f'(x)<0\) on \((12,16)\), there is a <strong>relative maximum</strong> on \(f\) at \(x=12\).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(b) Equation of the line tangent to \(g\) at \(x=8\)</div>
      <p>We use the point-slope form \(y-y_1=m(x-x_1)\). The slope of the tangent to \(g\) at \(x=8\) is \(g'(8)\).</p>
      <p>Given \(g(x)=(f(x))^2\), by the Chain Rule:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[g'(x)=2f(x)\cdot f'(x) \implies g'(8)=2f(8)\cdot f'(8)\]
      </div>
      <p>From the graph of \(f'\), the point \((8,2)\) lies on \(f'\), so \(f'(8)=\tfrac{1}{2}\). Thus:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[g'(8) = 2f(8)\!\left(\frac{1}{2}\right) = f(8)\]
      </div>
      <p>Find \(f(8)\) using \(f(0)=-3\) and the signed area under \(f'\) from 0 to 8:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[f(8)=f(0)+\int_0^8 f'(x)\,dx = -3+\tfrac{1}{2}(4)(2)+\tfrac{1}{2}(4)\!\left(\tfrac{1}{2}\right) = -3+4+1 = 2\]
      </div>
      <p>Therefore \(g'(8)=f(8)=2\) and \(g(8)=(f(8))^2=4\). The tangent line is:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[y-4=2(x-8) \implies \boxed{y=2x-12}\]
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(c) Critical numbers of \(h(x)=xe^{-0.25f(x)}\)</div>
      <p>Differentiate using the Product Rule and Chain Rule:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[h'(x)=e^{-0.25f(x)}+x\cdot\!\left(-0.25f'(x)\right)e^{-0.25f(x)} = e^{-0.25f(x)}\!\left(1-0.25x\,f'(x)\right)\]
      </div>
      <p>Since \(e^{-0.25f(x)}>0\) for all \(x\), setting \(h'(x)=0\) requires:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[1-0.25x\,f'(x)=0 \implies x\,f'(x)=4\]
      </div>
      <p>Reading points from the graph of \(f'\) to evaluate the product \(xf'(x)\):</p>
      <table style="border-collapse:collapse; margin:12px auto 16px; font-size:0.95rem; text-align:center;">
        <tr style="border-bottom:2px solid var(--rule);">
          <th style="padding:6px 18px; color:var(--muted);">\(x\)</th>
          <th style="padding:6px 18px; color:var(--muted);">\(f'(x)\)</th>
          <th style="padding:6px 18px; color:var(--muted);">\(xf'(x)\)</th>
        </tr>
        <tr><td style="padding:5px 18px;">0</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding:5px 18px;">2</td><td>2</td><td>4</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding:5px 18px;">4</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding:5px 18px;">8</td><td>\(\tfrac{1}{2}\)</td><td>4</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding:5px 18px;">12</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr>
        <tr style="border-top:1px solid var(--rule);"><td style="padding:5px 18px;">16</td><td>\(-\tfrac{1}{2}\)</td><td>\(-8\)</td></tr>
      </table>
      <p>The \(x\)-values satisfying \(xf'(x)=4\) are \(x=2\) and \(x=8\). These are the critical numbers of \(h(x)\).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(d) \(\displaystyle\int_4^8 xf''(x)\,dx\)</div>
      <p>Apply integration by parts with \(u=x\), \(dv=f''(x)\,dx\), so \(du=dx\) and \(v=f'(x)\):</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\int_4^8 xf''(x)\,dx = \Big[xf'(x)\Big]_4^8 - \int_4^8 f'(x)\,dx\]
      </div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[= \Big[xf'(x)-f(x)\Big]_4^8\]
      </div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[= \big(8f'(8)-f(8)\big)-\big(4f'(4)-f(4)\big)\]
      </div>
      <p>Reading values from the graph of \(f'\): \(f'(8)=\tfrac{1}{2}\), \(f'(4)=0\). Using values computed in (b): \(f(8)=2\). For \(f(4)\):</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[f(4)=f(0)+\int_0^4 f'(x)\,dx = -3+\tfrac{1}{2}(4)(2) = -3+4 = 1\]
      </div>
      <p>Substituting:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\left(8\cdot\tfrac{1}{2}-2\right)-\left(4\cdot 0-1\right) = (4-2)-(0-1) = 2+1 = \boxed{3}\]
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#top">↑ Return to top</a></div>
</div>

<!-- FR 5 -->
<div class="problem" id="fr5">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">FR 5</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Limits, Euler's Method, Separation of Variables</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Tangent to \(y=f(x)\) at \(x=0\) is \(y=4x+2\).</p>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(a) Evaluate the limit using series expansions</div>
      <p>From the tangent line \(y=4x+2\) at \(x=0\): \(f(0)=2\) and \(f'(0)=4\).</p>
      <p>Since \(g(x)=\displaystyle\int_0^x f(t)\,dt\), by FTC: \(g(0)=0\), \(g'(0)=f(0)=2\), \(g''(0)=f'(0)=4\). So:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[g(x) = 2x + 2x^2 + \cdots\]
      </div>
      <p>Expand the numerator using the Maclaurin series for \(\sin(2x)\):</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\sin(2x)-g(x) = \left(2x - \frac{4x^3}{3}+\cdots\right) - \left(2x+2x^2+\cdots\right) = -2x^2 + \text{higher-order terms}\]
      </div>
      <p>Expand the denominator:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[e^{3x}-\cos(2x)-3x = \left(1+3x+\frac{9x^2}{2}+\cdots\right)-\left(1-2x^2+\cdots\right)-3x = \frac{9x^2}{2}+2x^2+\cdots = \frac{13x^2}{2}+\cdots\]
      </div>
      <p>Both numerator and denominator have leading term \(x^2\), so dividing through by \(x^2\):</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{\sin(2x)-g(x)}{e^{3x}-\cos(2x)-3x} = \frac{-2}{13/2} = -\frac{4}{13}\]
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(b) Euler's method for \(\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\dfrac{y^2}{x+1}\), \(f(0)=2\), approximate \(f(1/2)\) with 2 steps</div>
      <p>Step size \(h=0.25\). Starting at \((0,2)\):</p>
      <p><strong>Step 1:</strong> \(f'(0)=\frac{4}{1}=4\). \(y_1=2+4(0.25)=3\) at \(x=0.25\).</p>
      <p><strong>Step 2:</strong> \(f'(0.25)=\frac{9}{1.25}=7.2\). \(y_2=3+7.2(0.25)=3+1.8=4.8\) at \(x=0.5\).</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[f\!\left(\tfrac{1}{2}\right)\approx 4.8\]
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(c) Separation of variables for \(\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\dfrac{y^2}{x+1}\), \(f(0)=2\)</div>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\frac{dy}{y^2}=\frac{dx}{x+1}\implies -\frac{1}{y}=\ln|x+1|+C\]
      </div>
      <p>At \(x=0,\,y=2\): \(-\tfrac{1}{2}=0+C\Rightarrow C=-\tfrac{1}{2}\).</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[-\frac{1}{y}=\ln(x+1)-\frac{1}{2}\implies y=\frac{1}{\frac{1}{2}-\ln(x+1)}=\frac{2}{1-2\ln(x+1)}\]
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="return-link"><a href="#top">↑ Return to top</a></div>
</div>

<!-- FR 6 -->
<div class="problem" id="fr6">
  <div class="problem-header">
    <span class="pnum">FR 6</span>
    <span class="topic-tag">Maclaurin Series — \(f(x)=\dfrac{1}{(1+x^2)^2}\)</span>
  </div>
  <div class="problem-body">
    <p>Maclaurin series for \(f(x)=\dfrac{1}{(1+x^2)^2}\) is given as \(1-2x^2+3x^4-4x^6+\cdots+(-1)^n(n+1)x^{2n}+\cdots\)</p>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(a) Use the series to find:</div>
      <p><strong>i. \(f^{(4)}(0)\):</strong></p>
      <p>The Maclaurin coefficient of \(x^4\) is \(\dfrac{f^{(4)}(0)}{4!}\). From the series, coefficient of \(x^4\) is \(3\).</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[f^{(4)}(0) = 3\cdot 4! = 3\cdot 24 = 72\]
      </div>
      <p><strong>ii. Coefficient of \(x^{22}\):</strong></p>
      <p>Set \(2n=22\Rightarrow n=11\). Coefficient: \((-1)^{11}(12) = -12\).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(b) Radius of convergence</div>
      <p>The series is built from \(\dfrac{1}{1+x^2}=\sum_{n=0}^\infty(-1)^n x^{2n}\), valid for \(|x^2|<1\), i.e., \(|x|<1\).</p>
      <p>Differentiating: the radius of convergence is preserved. <strong>\(R=1\).</strong></p>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-label">Ratio Test confirmation</div>
        <div class="math-display">
          \[\lim_{n\to\infty}\left|\frac{(n+2)x^{2n+2}}{(n+1)x^{2n}}\right|=x^2\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{n+2}{n+1}=x^2<1\implies|x|<1\]
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(c) Lagrange error bound for \(|f(0.5)-P(0.5)|\)</div>
      <p>Let \(P(x)\) be the fourth-degree Maclaurin polynomial: \(P(x)=1-2x^2+3x^4\).</p>
      <p>The error is bounded by the next term: \(|f(x)-P(x)|\leq|{-4x^6}|\) for \(|x|\leq 0.5\) (since the series is alternating with decreasing terms).</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[|f(0.5)-P(0.5)|\leq 4\cdot(0.5)^6 = 4\cdot\frac{1}{64}=\frac{1}{16}<\frac{1}{10}\checkmark\]
      </div>
      <p>Alternatively, using the graph of \(f^{(5)}\): \(\max_{|x|\leq 0.5}|f^{(5)}(x)|\approx 357.685\) (from the graph at \(x\approx 0.202\)).</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[|f(0.5)-P(0.5)|\leq\frac{M\cdot(0.5)^5}{5!}=\frac{357.685\cdot(0.031250)}{120}\approx\frac{11.178}{120}\approx 0.093<\frac{1}{10}\checkmark\]
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fr-part">
      <div class="fr-part-label">(d) Maclaurin series for \(\displaystyle\int_0^x\frac{1}{(1+t^2)^2}\,dt\)</div>
      <p>Integrate the series term by term:</p>
      <div class="math-display">
        \[\int_0^x\frac{1}{(1+t^2)^2}\,dt = x - \frac{2x^3}{3}+\frac{3x^5}{5}-\frac{4x^7}{7}+\cdots+\frac{(-1)^n(n+1)x^{2n+1}}{2n+1}+\cdots\]
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
